Abstract

SwiftAgg+ can significantly reduce the communication overheads without any compromise on security, and achieve optimal communication loads within diminishing gaps. Specifically, in presence of at most D=oâ€‹(N)ğ·ğ‘œğ‘D=o(N) dropout users, SwiftAgg+ achieves a per-user communication load of (1+ğ’ªâ€‹(1N))â€‹L1ğ’ª1ğ‘ğ¿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L symbols and a server communication load of (1+ğ’ªâ€‹(1N))â€‹L1ğ’ª1ğ‘ğ¿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L symbols, with a worst-case information-theoretic security guarantee, against any subset of up to T=oâ€‹(N)ğ‘‡ğ‘œğ‘T=o(N) semi-honest users who may also collude with the curious server. I Introduction

Federated learning (FL) is an emerging distributed learning framework that allows a group of distributed users (e.g., mobile devices) to collaboratively train a global model of size Lğ¿L with their local private data, without sharing the dataÂ [1, 2, 3]. Specifically, in a FL system with a central server and Nğ‘N users, during each training iteration, the server sends the current state of the global model to the users. Receiving the global model, each user then trains a local model with its local data, and sends the local model to the server. By aggregating the local models, the server can update the global model for the next iteration. While the local datasets are not directly shared with the server, several studies have shown that a curious server can launch model inversion attacks to reveal information about the training data of individual users from their local models (see, e.g.,Â [4, 5]). Therefore, the key challenge to protect usersâ€™ data privacy is to design secure aggregation protocols, which allow the aggregation of local models to be computed without revealing each individual model even if the server colludes with a limited number of users, called semi-honest users, in the system. Moreover, as some users may randomly drop out of the aggregation process (due to low batteries or unstable connections), the server should be able to robustly recover the aggregated local models of the surviving users in a privacy-preserving manner.

As such motivated, a secure aggregation protocol SecAgg is proposed inÂ [6]. In SecAgg, each pair of users agree on a shared random vector. In addition, each user generates a private random vector and secret shares it with other users. Before sending its local model to the server, each user masks the local model in a particular way. The mask is created based on the private and shared random vectors such that the shared part can be canceled out when aggregated at the server. In order to recover the result and cancel the remaining masks, the private random vector of each surviving user and the shared random vectors of each dropped user must be reconstructed using the collected shares from surviving users in the second round of communication.

Note that to have an information-theoretic security, the shared and the private random vectors must be chosen uniformly at random from vectors of size Lğ¿L. However, to make it practical in SecAgg, it is assumed that the users agree on common seeds for a pseudo-random generator rather than on the entire shared random vectors which is not secure in the context of information theory. In this paper, we focus on information-theoretic security guarantees.

One of the major challenges for SecAgg to scale up is the communication load. The secret sharing among users requires all-to-all communication, which incurs quadratic cost in the number of users Nğ‘N. There has been a series of works that aim to improve the communication efficiency of SecAggÂ (see, e.g.,Â [7, 8, 9]). InÂ [7], TurboAgg is proposed to perform secure aggregation following a circular topology, achieving a communication load of ğ’ªâ€‹(Lâ€‹Nâ€‹logâ¡N)ğ’ªğ¿ğ‘ğ‘\mathcal{O}(LN\log N) at the server and ğ’ªâ€‹(Lâ€‹logâ¡N)ğ’ªğ¿ğ‘\mathcal{O}(L\log N) at each user. The idea of TurboAgg is partitioning the users into several groups each of size ğ’ªâ€‹(logâ¡N)ğ’ªğ‘\mathcal{O}(\log N) to accelerate model aggregation phase. To protect individual models, each user masks its local model in a particular way. Furthermore, the masked local models are encoded using Lagrange coded computing [10] such that the data of dropped users can be recovered at each stage of the protocol. Each user in a group computes the aggregation of the masked models and the aggregation of coded models of all users in the previous groups, and sends them to all users in the next group, as well as the masked and coded version of its model. The missing terms of aggregated masked models, caused by the dropped users, can be recovered in the next group if at least half of the users in a group do not drop out. TurboAgg guarantees the privacy of individual local models with high probability as long as the number of semi-honest users is less than N/2ğ‘2N/2.

In [8], SecAgg+ is proposed which considers a kğ‘˜k-regular communication graph among users instead of the complete graph used in SecAgg to reduce the communication and computation loads, where k=ğ’ªâ€‹(logâ¡N)ğ‘˜ğ’ªğ‘k=\mathcal{O}(\log N). It means that each user secret shares with a subset of other users instead of sharing with all of them. It is shown that SecAgg+ requires a communication of ğ’ªâ€‹(Lâ€‹N+Nâ€‹logâ¡N)ğ’ªğ¿ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘\mathcal{O}(LN+N\log N) at the server and ğ’ªâ€‹(L+logâ¡N)ğ’ªğ¿ğ‘\mathcal{O}(L+\log N) at each user. InÂ [9], another similar idea, CCESA, is proposed in which a sparse random graph is used as communication network instead of the complete graph. Thus, secret sharing is used for a subset of users instead of all-to-all communication. While SecAgg+, TurboAgg and CCESA improve the communication efficiency of SecAgg, they only provide probabilistic privacy guarantees as opposed to the worst-case guarantee of SecAgg.

Some other secure aggregation protocols focus on reducing the computation complexity of SecAgg, rather than the communication load. FastSecAgg is proposed in [11] which presents a multi-secret sharing scheme based on a finite field version of the Fast Fourier Transform to achieve a trade-off between the number of secrets, the dropout tolerance and the privacy threshold. FastSecAgg reduces the computation load of the server as well as per-user to ğ’ªâ€‹(Lâ€‹logâ¡N)ğ’ªğ¿ğ‘\mathcal{O}(L\log N), while achieves the same order of communication as SecAgg with lower privacy threshold and dropout tolerance.

In Â [12], LightSecAgg is proposed to reduce the computation complexity bottleneck in secure aggregation. In LightSecAgg, each user independently samples a random mask, encodes it using Tğ‘‡T-private MDS (maximum distance separable) coding, generating secret shares of the mask to send to other users. Then, each user adds mask to its local model and sends the masked model to the server. The server can reconstruct and cancel out the aggregated mask of surviving users via a one-shot decoding, using the aggregated coded masks received in a second phase of communication with surviving users. Similar idea of one-shot reconstruction of aggregated mask was also utilized in [13], which nevertheless requires a trusted third party, and much more randomness needs to be generated, as well as more storage at each user.

As an earlier and conference version of this manuscript, in [14] , we propose SwiftAgg which reduces the server communication load via partitioning users into several groups and using Shamirâ€™s secret sharing [15] to keep the local models private. SwiftAgg is able to achieve correct aggregation in presence of up to Dğ·D dropout users, with formally-proven the worst-case security guarantee against up to Tğ‘‡T semi-honest users. Independently, similar ideas have been used in CodedSecAgg [16], but dropout users in groups have not been addressed and there is no formal definition and proof of privacy. The communication loads and the computation loads of the existing approaches are compared in TableÂ I.

In this paper, we propose SwiftAgg+ as a new scheme for secure aggregation in federated learning, which is robust against up to Dğ·D user dropouts and achieves worst-case security guarantees against up to T<Nâˆ’Dğ‘‡ğ‘ğ·T<N-D semi-honest users which may collude with each other as well as with the server to gain some information. In SwiftAgg+, in order to compute the aggregation of local models in a privacy-preserving manner, the number of symbols received by the server is (1+ğ’ªâ€‹(1N))â€‹L1ğ’ª1ğ‘ğ¿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L as long as T=oâ€‹(N)ğ‘‡ğ‘œğ‘T=o(N) and Nâˆ’D=ğ’ªâ€‹(N)ğ‘ğ·ğ’ªğ‘N-D=\mathcal{O}(N). In addition, the number of symbols sent by each user is (1+ğ’ªâ€‹(1N))â€‹L1ğ’ª1ğ‘ğ¿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L, for T=oâ€‹(N)ğ‘‡ğ‘œğ‘T=o(N) and D=oâ€‹(N)ğ·ğ‘œğ‘D=o(N).

Moreover, since in federated learning many of the users may not be accessible from each other, the number of active communication links, among users or from users to the server, is also an important factor when designing secure aggregation protocols. SwiftAgg+ allows for a flexible trade-off between the communication loads and the network connections. To achieve this trade-off, we first partition the users into groups of size T+D+Kğ‘‡ğ·ğ¾T+D+K for some Kâˆˆâ„•ğ¾â„•K\in\mathbb{N} (See Fig.Â 4), and the groups are arranged on an arbitrary hierarchical tree with the server as the root. Then in the first phase, each user partitions its local model into Kğ¾K parts. In the second phase, users within each group secret share the partitions of their local models using ramp secret sharing [17], and aggregate the shares locally. In the third phase, each user aggregates in-group shares and the messages received from the corresponding users in its children groups and sends the result to the corresponding user in its parent group, which is finally sent to the server. In the third phase, if one user in a group drops out, the rest of the users in the sequence that includes the dropped user remain silent. This aggregation tree provides flexibility to adjust the delay of each iteration of training process based on the network connections. Additionally, parameter Kğ¾K controls the trade-off between communication loads and network connectivity which can be chosen based on the constraints of the network.

SwiftAgg+ simultaneously achieves the following advantages compared to the existing works:

  1. 1.

    For T=oâ€‹(N)ğ‘‡ğ‘œğ‘T=o(N) and Nâˆ’D=ğ’ªâ€‹(N)ğ‘ğ·ğ’ªğ‘N-D=\mathcal{O}(N), the server communication load in SwiftAgg+ is within factor 1 of the cut-set lower bound.

  2. 2.

    SwiftAgg+ has the flexibility to reduce the number of active connections between the users at the cost of increasing the communication load away from the optimum.

  3. 3.

    It is resilient to up to Dğ·D user dropouts. As opposed to the existing schemes, in SwiftAgg+, due to the structure of the scheme, the effects of user dropouts are already handled in one round of communication with the server, and there is no need to take place another round of communication.

  4. 4.

    It achieves worst-case information-theoretic security against a curious server and any subset of up to T<Nâˆ’Dğ‘‡ğ‘ğ·T<N-D semi-honest users.

  5. 5.

    Based on the possible connections among users, SwiftAgg+ have a flexibility to control the delay of each training iteration.

III Main results

In this section, we present our main results on per-user and server communication loads, achieved by the proposed SwiftAgg+ scheme. Note that the operations are done in a finite field, which is large enough to avoid hitting the boundary in the process of aggregation. Remark 1:

Note that the case T=oâ€‹(N)ğ‘‡ğ‘œğ‘T=o(N) is well justified. Restricted with a limited budget, it often becomes prohibitively difficult for the adversary to hack a constant fraction of the users as the number of users grows. For example, it is seems easier to hack one of only two users rather than 50 out of 100 ones.

As the number of active communication links is important in federated learning, SwiftAgg+ also allows us to reduce the number of active network connections in the secure aggregation problem at the cost of increasing the communication load away from the optimum. The result is presented in the following theorem.

Remark 2:

In (4) by increasing parameter Kğ¾K, both per-user communication load and server communication load are reduced, while the number of active connections in the achievable scheme |â„°ğ’œK|subscriptâ„°subscriptğ’œğ¾|\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}_{K}}| is increased and vice versa. To achieve the trade-off between communication loads and network connections |â„°ğ’œK|subscriptâ„°subscriptğ’œğ¾|\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}_{K}}|, SwiftAgg+ partitions the users into some disjoint groups, each of size K+D+Tğ¾ğ·ğ‘‡K+D+T users labeled as user 111 to user K+D+Tğ¾ğ·ğ‘‡K+D+T of that group. The NK+D+Tğ‘ğ¾ğ·ğ‘‡\frac{N}{K+D+T} groups are arranged in an arbitrary tree with the server as the root. The model aggregation starts from the leaves of the tree, and proceeds in three main phases: Phase 1: Each user partitions the vector of its local model of length Lğ¿L into Kğ¾K sub-vectors of length LKğ¿ğ¾\frac{L}{K}, Phase 2: Each user uses a ramp sharingÂ [17] to share the sub-vectors of its model to other users within its group, Phase 3: Each user aggregates the shares that it receives in Phase 2 and also adds it to the messages received from the corresponding users in its children groups and sends the result to the corresponding user in its parent group. These messages are finally reach to the server and are used to recover the aggregated local models.

While in problem formulation we let Lâ†’âˆâ†’ğ¿L\to\infty, the proposed scheme works for finite values of Lğ¿L, where K|Lconditionalğ¾ğ¿K|L. If Kâˆ¤Lnot-dividesğ¾ğ¿K\nmid L, we can zero-pad the local models.

VI Theoretical Analysis

In this section, we analyze the communication and computation complexities of the proposed SwiftAgg+ scheme, and provide an information-theoretic proof on its privacy guarantee in protecting local model information from colluding users and the server.

VI-A Communication Loads and Number of Active Connections

According to (12), the total number of symbols that are needed to be received by the server is T+Kğ‘‡ğ¾T+K, each of size LKğ¿ğ¾\frac{L}{K}. Thus, the normalized server communication load in SwiftAgg+ is Rserver(L)=1+TK.superscriptsubscriptğ‘…serverğ¿1ğ‘‡ğ¾R_{\text{server}}^{(L)}=1+\frac{T}{K}.

In each group, at most Î½â€‹(Î½âˆ’1)ğœˆğœˆ1\nu(\nu-1) symbols are sent by the members, each of size LKğ¿ğ¾\frac{L}{K}, and there are NÎ½ğ‘ğœˆ\frac{N}{\nu} groups. In addition, at most Î½ğœˆ\nu symbols are sent from a child group to a parent group. VII conclusion

In this paper, we propose SwiftAgg+, a secure aggregation protocol for model aggregation in federated learning, which acheives a trade-off between the communication loads and network connections. Via partitioning the users into groups, careful designs of intra and inter group secret sharing and aggregation method, SwiftAgg+ is able to achieve correct aggregation in presence of up to Dğ·D dropout users, with the worst-case security guarantee against up to Tğ‘‡T users colluding with a curious server. Moreover, SwiftAgg+ has a flexibility to control the delay of each training iteration by choosing the aggregation tree with different depth. Compared with previous secure aggregation protocols, SwiftAgg+ significantly slashes the communication load. For T=oâ€‹(N)ğ‘‡ğ‘œğ‘T=o(N) and Nâˆ’D=ğ’ªâ€‹(N)ğ‘ğ·ğ’ªğ‘N-D=\mathcal{O}(N), in terms of the number of required bits, the server communication load in SwiftAgg+ is within factor 1 of the cut-set lower bound. In addition, in the case of local models with uniform distributions, the per-user communication load in SwiftAgg+ is within factor logâ„“â¡â„“â€‹Nsubscriptâ„“â„“ğ‘\log_{\ell}{\ell N} of the cut-set lower bound as long as T=oâ€‹(N)ğ‘‡ğ‘œğ‘T=o(N) and D=oâ€‹(N)ğ·ğ‘œğ‘D=o(N).
